SIMPLE: roulette
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Roulette
<hw>Rou*lette"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., properly, a
little wheel or ball. See <er>Rouleau</er>, <er>Roll</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A game of chance, in which a small ball is made to move
round rapidly on a circle divided off into numbered red and black
spaces, the one on which it stops indicating the result of a variety of
wagers permitted by the game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A small toothed
wheel used by engravers to roll over a plate in order to order to
produce rows of dots.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A similar wheel used to
roughen the surface of a plate, as in making alterations in a
mezzotint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>the curve traced by any point in
the plane of a given curve when the latter rolls, without sliding, over
another fixed curve. See <er>Cycloid</er>, and
<er>Epycycloid</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A small toothed wheel used to make short incisions
in paper, as a sheet of postage stamps to facilitate their
separation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Roulette</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Roulette
<hw>Rou*lette"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make short incisions in
with a roulette; to separate by incisions made with a roulette; <as>as,
to <ex>roulette</ex> a sheet of postage stamps</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rouly-pouly</ent>⟦br⟧
